00:00:01.229 --> 00:00:05.230
Chahoa intended married couples to work together.

00:00:05.230 --> 00:00:11.230
That's why Jesus used the expression we find at Matthew 19 and verse 6.

00:00:11.230 --> 00:00:17.230
Let's read this from the Bible, Matthew 19, I'll give you a moment,

00:00:17.230 --> 00:00:24.640
Matthew chapter 19, and we're going to read verse 6.

00:00:24.640 --> 00:00:30.640
Now, first of all, Jesus quotes from Genesis 2.24.

00:00:30.640 --> 00:00:36.640
He says, speaking of varied couples, he says, so that they are no longer two, but one flesh.

00:00:36.640 --> 00:00:41.640
Now, you remember Chahoa made that comment in the Garden of Eden.

00:00:41.640 --> 00:00:45.640
But now, Jesus adds something that isn't in Genesis.

00:00:45.640 --> 00:00:56.640
He says, therefore, what God has yoked together, let no man put apart.

00:00:57.640 --> 00:01:04.640
When we think of a yoke, we may think of a team of horses plowing a field or pulling a heavy wagon.

00:01:04.640 --> 00:01:08.640
Now, if they pull together, they can be a powerful force.

00:01:08.640 --> 00:01:14.049
The same is true when family members work together.

00:01:14.049 --> 00:01:22.049
Mom, dad, you have excellent reasons to work together.

00:01:22.049 --> 00:01:26.049
When you work together, you contribute to the peace of the family.

00:01:26.049 --> 00:01:29.049
And think of the effect it has on the children.

00:01:29.049 --> 00:01:35.049
By working together, you are teaching that fine young son of yours how to be a caring husband and father,

00:01:35.049 --> 00:01:41.049
and your beautiful daughter, how to be a supportive wife and mother.

00:01:41.049 --> 00:01:47.049
But what happens when teammates begin pulling in opposite directions or when one puts on the brakes?

00:01:47.049 --> 00:01:49.049
Let's watch a video.

00:01:49.049 --> 00:01:51.049
Now, here's the setup.

